O God! Thou art my God alone;
Before the dawn, before the stone
Was rolled away from earth and tomb,
I reached for solace through the gloom.

No other voice, no other name,
Could stoke my hope or fan my flame;
And in the hush before the sun,
I find my heart and Thine are one.

Let all the noise of earth recede;
Let silence answer every need;
O God, my God, my soul has known
Thou art my God, and mine alone.

O God! Thou art my God alone;  
No other voice upon the stone,  
No shadow cast upon the ground,  
No rival echo can resound.  
Thy silence brims with hidden fire,  
Thy mercy shapes my sole desire;  
I wander far, yet still I see  
The path that leads me back to Thee.  
O God! Thou art my God alone;  
In every loss, in every moan.

Farewell, thou child of my right hand, and joy;
Your laughter lingers in the empty room,
A distant bell, a half-remembered tune,
A hope that time cannot wholly destroy.
Your footprints fade in dust that will not stay;
The bed is cool, the window’s light is wan,
Yet somewhere, in a sun-drenched field, you run,
Not lost, but drifting gently far away.
I keep the echo, though the voice is gone;
Farewell, my child, bright as the waking dawn.
